    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Keyword cannibalization</strong> occurs when multiple pages on the same website target the same primary keyword, forcing them to compete against each other in search results. This splits link equity across competing pages, creates ranking instability as Google alternates which page to show, and often causes neither page to rank as well as a single consolidated page would. Ahrefs research shows <strong>17% of websites have significant cannibalization issues</strong> affecting their top-ranking keywords.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Prevalence</div>
            <div class="tms-value">17% of sites (Ahrefs)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Keyword Research</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Primary fix</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Consolidate via 301 redirect</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Cannibalization is one of the most prevalent SEO issues, yet it frequently goes undetected until ranking fluctuations appear or the wrong page starts outranking a primary conversion page. The problem compounds as a site grows — without structured keyword mapping, overlapping topics naturally accumulate over time.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is keyword cannibalization?</h2>
        <p>Keyword cannibalization happens when two or more pages on a site pursue the same primary keyword and Google can't determine which page should rank for it. Instead of picking a winner, Google may alternate between them — causing position fluctuations — or suppress both in favor of a competitor's single authoritative page.</p>
        <p>The problem intensifies with content volume. A site publishing 5 articles per month for 3 years has 180 articles. Without keyword mapping, multiple articles will inevitably target overlapping queries. The longer this goes unchecked, the more URLs are splitting the authority that should be concentrated in one.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">When cannibalization is NOT a problem</div>
          <p>If two pages from the same site appear in positions 1 and 3 for the same query, that's SERP dominance — a sign of strong topical authority. Cannibalization becomes a problem when competing pages are at positions 6 and 9, and consolidating them would likely push the winner to positions 2-4.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why keyword cannibalization damages rankings</h2>
        <p>Cannibalization fragments the SEO signals that should be concentrated in one authoritative page. Four specific harms:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Diluted link equity.</strong> Backlinks that should reinforce one page disperse across multiple competing URLs. Each page receives a fraction of the authority a consolidated page would accumulate.</li>
          <li><strong>Ranking instability.</strong> Google alternates which page it shows for the query, producing day-to-day position fluctuations that make performance tracking unreliable and user experience inconsistent.</li>
          <li><strong>Wrong page ranking.</strong> A blog post may outrank a product page for a commercial keyword — sending informational-intent traffic to a page that was meant to convert buyers.</li>
          <li><strong>Wasted crawl budget.</strong> Google processes multiple pages targeting identical intent when one would suffice. On large sites, this means lower-priority pages get crawled at the expense of new content.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How to find and fix keyword cannibalization</h2>

        <h3>Step 1 — Detect the cannibalization</h3>
        <p>Three methods, in order of reliability:</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Method 1: Google SERP check</span><br>
          site:yourdomain.com "<span class="uf-new">target keyword</span>"<br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># If 2+ pages appear, potential cannibalization</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Method 2: Google Search Console</span><br>
          Performance → Filter by Query → check which URLs get impressions<br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Impression splitting across 2+ pages = confirmed cannibalization</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Method 3: Keyword mapping audit</span><br>
          Export all URLs + target keywords<br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Find duplicate primary keywords — each should appear once only</span>
        </div>

        <h3>Step 2 — Choose your fix</h3>
        <p>There are four options, each appropriate for different situations:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Consolidate via 301 redirect</strong> — best when both pages target the same intent and audience. Merge the weaker page's best content into the stronger one, then 301 redirect the weaker URL.</li>
          <li><strong>Differentiate by intent</strong> — best when the pages serve slightly different needs. Rewrite one page to target a distinct intent or keyword cluster so they no longer compete.</li>
          <li><strong>Set canonical tags</strong> — best when both pages must remain accessible but one should rank. Add a canonical pointing to the preferred page on the duplicate.</li>
          <li><strong>Strengthen with internal links</strong> — as a supplementary signal. Point multiple internal links at the preferred page using the target keyword as anchor text.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">Types of cannibalization by cause</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Cannibalization type</th><th>Common cause</th><th>Best fix</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Blog vs feature page</strong></td>
                <td>Blog post targets the same keyword as a product page</td>
                <td class="cell-yes">Differentiate by intent — blog informs, page converts</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Old vs new post</strong></td><td>New article published without auditing existing content</td><td class="cell-meh">Merge into the older, higher-authority URL</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Category vs product</strong></td><td>Category and product page share primary keyword</td><td class="cell-meh">Make category more topical; product more specific</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Location pages</strong></td><td>Multiple city pages target same keyword without location modifier</td><td class="cell-no">Add strong location signals to each page</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Tag vs category page</strong></td><td>WordPress tag and category both target the same keyword</td><td>Noindex tag pages; let category rank</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real keyword cannibalization examples and fixes</h2>

        <h3>Example 1 — SaaS blog vs feature page</h3>
        <p>A CRM company maintained two separate pages: a blog post titled "What is Lead Scoring?" and a feature page "Lead Scoring Software" — both optimized for the keyword "lead scoring." Google couldn't determine which to rank, and neither reached the top 10. The team consolidated: merged the blog's explanatory content into the feature page, redirected the old blog URL with a 301, and updated internal links to point to the surviving page. Within 6 weeks, the feature page hit position 3 — capturing both informational and commercial traffic in one URL.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — Local business redundant service pages</h3>
        <p>A plumbing service ran two pages: "/services/drain-cleaning" and "/drain-cleaning-services" — both targeting "drain cleaning [city]." Neither ranked on page 1. After redirecting the weaker page to the stronger one and pointing 8 internal links at the surviving URL with "drain cleaning" as anchor text, rankings improved from position 14 to position 5 within 6 weeks.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Keyword cannibalization vs duplicate content — what's the difference?</h2>
        <p>These are related but distinct problems with different root causes and fixes.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Keyword cannibalization</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Multiple pages target the same keyword</li>
              <li>Content may be different but intent overlaps</li>
              <li>Caused by poor keyword mapping</li>
              <li>Fix: differentiate or consolidate pages</li>
              <li>Detected in Search Console impressions</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Duplicate content</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Same or near-identical text on multiple URLs</li>
              <li>Content is the same — not just intent</li>
              <li>Caused by pagination, URL parameters, scrapers</li>
              <li>Fix: canonical tags, 301 redirects, noindex</li>
              <li>Detected in site:domain.com search or crawl tools</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices to prevent keyword cannibalization</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Maintain a keyword map.</strong> A spreadsheet mapping one primary keyword to one URL is the single most effective prevention tool. Before publishing, check the map. If the keyword already has a URL, update that page instead of creating a new one.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit before publishing new content.</strong> Run a quick site:domain.com "target keyword" check before every new article. Takes 30 seconds and catches conflicts before they're indexed.</li>
          <li><strong>Run a full cannibalization audit quarterly.</strong> Export all URLs and target keywords from Search Console. Sort by query — duplicates surface immediately. For sites publishing 20+ articles per month, this is a mandatory monthly task.</li>
          <li><strong>Differentiate by intent, not just title.</strong> Two articles on "email marketing" can coexist if one targets "email marketing for e-commerce" and the other targets "email marketing for B2B SaaS" — different intent, different audience, no overlap.</li>
          <li><strong>Use internal linking to signal authority.</strong> The page you want to rank should receive the most internal links with the most keyword-specific anchor text. Signal Google's ranking preference through your own link architecture.</li>
          <li><strong>Build content around clusters, not individual keywords.</strong> A cluster approach — one pillar page per topic, multiple supporting posts targeting subtopics — naturally prevents cannibalization because each piece occupies a distinct slice of the topic.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — redirecting all duplicates to the homepage</div>
          <p>When consolidating cannibalized pages, don't redirect the losers to the homepage. Google treats that as a soft 404 and passes no equity. Always redirect to the most topically relevant surviving URL. If no good match exists, consider a 410 Gone instead.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common keyword cannibalization mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Treating all cannibalization as equally urgent.</strong> Two pages at positions 7 and 12 for the same keyword need consolidation. Two pages at positions 1 and 4 probably don't — leave the dominance.</li>
          <li><strong>Merging without redirecting.</strong> Deleting the weaker page without a 301 redirect destroys any link equity and creates a 404 for anyone who bookmarked the old URL.</li>
          <li><strong>Conflating cannibalization with low rankings.</strong> If a page ranks poorly, that might be a content quality or link authority issue — not cannibalization. Diagnose before treating.</li>
          <li><strong>Fixing cannibalization but not internal links.</strong> After consolidation, update all internal links pointing to the old URL. Leaving them pointing to a redirected URL wastes crawl budget and sends equity through an extra hop.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is keyword cannibalization always bad?</span>
