            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Run a site:yourdomain.com "target keyword" search in Google. Multiple page appearances suggest cannibalization. Also use Google Search Console's Performance report — filter by query to see which URLs capture impressions for that keyword. Impression splitting across multiple pages signals confirmed cannibalization.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How do I fix keyword cannibalization?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>The main options are: (1) consolidate competing pages with a 301 redirect from the weaker to the stronger page, (2) differentiate pages by targeting distinct keyword clusters, (3) set a canonical tag pointing to the preferred page, or (4) use internal linking to signal which page should rank.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can internal linking fix cannibalization?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Partially. Strong internal linking to the preferred page signals to Google which URL should rank. However, when both pages have comparable content and intent, internal links alone are insufficient. Consolidation or differentiation typically needs to be implemented.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
